TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));

The solution of the linear system
\[
\begin{array}{rrrcr}
x &+2y &-5z &=& 1 \\
2x &-2y &+z&=& 2 \\
4x &-2y &+3z&=& 3 \\
\end{array}
\]

The solution of this system is 
$BR
\(x=\) \{ ans_rule(6) \},
EOT
&ANS(num_cmp("5/7"));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
\(y=\) \{ ans_rule(6) \}, and
EOT
&ANS(num_cmp("-11/28"));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
\(z=\) \{ ans_rule(6) \}.
EOT
&ANS(num_cmp("-3/14"));


TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));
$BR Hint: 
Modify your solution of the preceding problem.
EOT

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));
$BR $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD
We obtain
\[
\begin{array}{lrrrrr}
\hbox{equation} & x & y & z & RHS & RS \\
{[1]} & 1 & 2 & -5 & 1 & -1 \\
{[2]} & 2 & -2 & 1 & 2 & 3 \\
{[3]} & 4 & -2 & 3 & 3 & 8 \\
{[4]=[2]-2[1]}  & 0 & -6 & 11 & 0 & 5 \\
{[5]=[3]-4[1]} & 0 & -10 & 23 & -1 & 12 \\
{[6]=6[5]-10[4]} & 0 & 0 & 28 & -6 & 24 \\
\end{array}
\]


The last equation is \(28z=-6\) which gives \(\underline{z=-\frac{3}{14}}\).
Substituting \(z\) in equation \([4]\) gives
\(-6y-\frac{33}{14}=0\) or \(\underline{y=-\frac{11}{28}}\). Substituting \(y\) and \(z\) in
equation \([1]\) gives \(x-\frac{11}{14}+\frac{15}{14} = 1\) or 
\(\underline{x=\frac{5}{7}}\).

EOT



